 1248: 
 1249: **The outcome measure is a bounded, non-distributional aggregate.** The value
 1250: the model scores is a cardinal utilitarian-style sum over affected parties on a
 1251: bounded, infrastructure-like public-investment slice; it is not distributionally
 1252: weighted and says nothing about redistribution, equity, or who bears benefits and
 1253: harms. A portfolio can score well on this measure while distributing badly.
 1254: Applying the criterion across groups, or to the whole budget or the purpose of
 1255: taxation, would require a separate social-welfare and incidence specification this
 1256: paper does not provide. The model is also partial-equilibrium: strategic
 1257: reporting, endogenous proposal supply, project complementarities, tax incidence,
 1258: and general-equilibrium effects are outside it (see the
 1259: [claim-and-estimand-contract](../research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md)).
 1260: 
 1261: **Epistemically, this is one team's self-critiqued design.** The
 1262: adversarial corpus was produced by the same research effort it attacks,
 1263: with AI assistance; the earlier apparatus's status-quo baseline was
 1264: audit-parameterized (its parameters drawn item-by-item from published
 1265: audit-institution findings, with primary-source verification still in progress), while the current symmetry gate is an uncalibrated
 1266: stylized selection test — neither is calibrated to a specific PB dataset,
 1267: and the remaining parameters are plausible rather than measured; and no
 1268: pilot has been run. The three missing validations — independent expert
 1269: attack, calibration to empirical PB data, and a bounded tutored pilot
 1270: (sports-sector, one municipality) — are the research program's next
 1271: phase, in that order.
