research/audit-evidence-base.md:1:# Audit-Institution Evidence Base for the E7 Calibrated Baseline
research/audit-evidence-base.md:5:Evidence base assembled 2026-07-04 under the rule of [[105_CALIBRATED_BASELINE_EVIDENCE_AND_A036_RESOLUTION|docs/105_CALIBRATED_BASELINE_EVIDENCE_AND_A036_RESOLUTION.md]]: the E7 institutional-baseline arm (S′) must be parameterized from published findings of supreme audit institutions and ex-post evaluation bodies, spanning several countries and political orientations, with per-item citations, category matching (construction/infrastructure findings calibrate construction arms; transfer/social-program findings calibrate transfer arms), a declared band, and the chosen operating point stated in the E7 write-up — not here. This document declares the band; the operating points are selected and justified when E7 is implemented, and the author reviews the mapping before any run.
research/audit-evidence-base.md:7:Method: three parallel research sweeps (Andean: Chile, Peru, Colombia; Atlantic Latin America: Brazil, Mexico, Argentina; high-capacity comparators: United States, United Kingdom, European Union), each instructed to report only findings attributable to a named audit or evaluation institution, to tag category explicitly, and to label verification status honestly. Items are labeled **[P]** where the primary institutional source was read directly, and **[S]** where the figure is corroborated across multiple outlets citing the institution but the primary document was not opened; every [S] item carrying weight in the E7 parameterization enters the verification queue below before formal citation.
research/audit-evidence-base.md:41:- **[S→P queue]** TCU, *Diagnóstico de Obras Paralisadas* (operational audit and continuing panel, 2018-19 onward). Category: construction. Of ~21,000 federally funded works that should be in execution, **more than 8,600 (~41%) paralyzed or unfinished**, with R$8.2+ billion already invested in them. Informs: the reported-vs-real completion analogue for works — the single most direct calibration item for the construction arm's non-delivery share. <https://portal.tcu.gov.br/biblioteca-digital/auditoria-operacional-sobre-obras-paralisadas.htm>
research/audit-evidence-base.md:43:- **[S→P queue]** CGU, *Programa de Fiscalização em Entes Federativos* (municipal audit lotteries since 2003; >2,200 audits). Category: transfers/social programs. Reported synthesis: ~73% of audited administrations with irregularities; **~8.2% of federal transfers not applied as intended** — the direct candidate for the transfer arm's leakage level. Level figures are secondary until confirmed against the primary descriptive statistics in Avis, Ferraz and Finan (2018). <https://www.gov.br/cgu/pt-br/assuntos/auditoria-e-fiscalizacao/programa-de-fiscalizacao-em-entes-federativos>
research/audit-evidence-base.md:49:- **[S]** ASF, *recuperaciones operadas* series. Category: cross-cutting. Historical (CP 2007-2010): **64.2% of determined-recoverable amounts actually recovered**; recovery capacity down >80% since 2018, with recent sector recoveries in the low single digits of observed amounts. Informs: the recovery parameter r — a wide band whose denominators differ (determined-recoverable vs observed), to be handled explicitly in the E7 write-up. <https://www.asf.gob.mx/Section/62_Recuperaciones>
research/audit-evidence-base.md:66:- **[S→P queue]** CGR Perú, *Obras Paralizadas* series (Infobras). December 2023: **2,298 paralyzed works**; ~S/13 billion already spent (≈48% of their cost executed with no delivered use value). December 2024: 2,476 works, S/43.1 billion (definition: 6+ months without physical progress); causes led by contract breach (25.4%) and lack of funds (21.2%). Category: construction. Informs: reported-vs-real completion and the sunk-spend share of the works arm; two consecutive years give temporal robustness.
research/audit-evidence-base.md:67:- **[S→P queue]** CGR Colombia, *elefantes blancos / obras inconclusas*. 2023: 1,753 works flagged (COP 15.2 trillion), of which **1,054 strictly unfinished "elefantes blancos" (COP 7.02 trillion)** — the strict subset is the calibration item; 2024: 1,700+ works ≈COP 6 trillion. Category: construction.
research/audit-evidence-base.md:68:- **[S→P queue]** CGR Colombia, *VISR rural housing subsidies audit* (execution 2000-2019). Category: **transfers/social** — the one robust Colombian transfer item: of 10,000+ subsidies granted, **only ~24% culminated** in completed homes; fiscal findings COP ~9.7 billion, six with presumed penal implication. Informs: reported-vs-real delivery in a transfer program — a 76-point delivery gap inside a formally controlled scheme.
